Data Preprocessing Conclusions¶

Conclusion on missing values

  • The amount and impact of missing values differ between columns - this along with the first 20 rows suggests there is not an obvious pattern as to why the values are missing
    • Possible reasons for missing data:
      • these categories were not required when posting an ad
      • the information was unknown
      • entry or data collection errors
  • Aside from is_4wd imputing values in the model_year, cylinders, odometer, and paint_color columns may impact the trend of the data because they are contributing to 10% or more of the values and could be filled in with incorrect information if the mean or median are used
    • For example the median of model_year may be older than the year the vehicle missing a value was made

Conclusion on duplicate values

  • The data does not contain duplicate rows

Conclusion on data types

  • is_4wd column changed from float to int
  • date_posted column changed from object to datetime
  • Although there are more columns with float data types and would be more appropriate as int data types, they are missing values and cannot be changed to int data type due to the missing values

Reviewer Comment ¶

Success: The conclusion is written in detail👍

Reviewer Comment ¶

Remark:

You are right (about columns model_year, cylinders, odometer): filling in missing values with simply a median or mean by a column is a rather risky strategy and is only acceptable for cases where no more than 10% of the data is missing in our dataframe.

Some valuable advice: the other good option here is to find a median values for different 'model' groups and fill missing values for each group separately (it is about missing values in 'model_year, cylinders, odometer').

Missing values can lead to distortion of the analysis results, that is why it is so important to preprocess them.

Student Comment/Response to comment above:

Thank you for the suggestion of the alternative option with using median values for each model group. I didnt even think of that!

Requested information to be added to the data

Plan of action

  • Use the series.dt.day_name() method to extract the week day from date_posted column
  • Use pandas.series.dt.month() method to extract the month from date_posted column
    • May need to change this to a more readable value (month number -> month name)
  • Use the pandas.series.dt.year() method to extract the year from date_posted column
  • age of vehicle when ad was posted = ad posted year found above - model_year
  • average mileage/year = odometer / age of vehicle when ad was posted
  • Create a function to assign the numerical ranking for the condition column

In [29]:
# Create a column for the day of the week the ad was posted
vehicle_ads['weekday_posted'] = vehicle_ads['date_posted'].dt.day_name()

# Create a column for the month the ad was posted
vehicle_ads['month_posted'] = vehicle_ads['date_posted'].dt.month

# Create a column for the year the ad was posted
vehicle_ads['year_posted'] = vehicle_ads['date_posted'].dt.year

# Create a column for the age of the vehicle when it was posted
vehicle_ads['age'] = vehicle_ads['year_posted'] - vehicle_ads['model_year']

# Create a function to handle vehicles that are 0 years old
def mileage(row):
    try:
        if row['age'] > 0:
            mileage_per_year =  row['odometer'] / row['age']
            return mileage_per_year
        else:
            return row['odometer']
    except:
        print('Something didnt work')
        
# Create a column for the mileage/year
vehicle_ads['mileage_per_year'] = vehicle_ads.apply(mileage, axis=1)

Create a function to assign numerical rank for the condition column

# Create a function to assign a numerical rank for the statements in condition column
def assign_condition_rank(condition):
    if condition == 'new':
        return 5
    if condition == 'like new':
        return 4
    if condition == 'excellent':
        return 3
    if condition == 'good':
        return 2
    if condition == 'fair':
        return 1
    if condition == 'salvage':
        return 0
    else:
        return 'condition unknown'
    
# Create a new column for the condition rank    
vehicle_ads['condition_rank'] = vehicle_ads['condition'].apply(assign_condition_rank)

In [36]:
# Create a function to calculate IQR and related stats for columns
def find_outliers(column):
    min_value = column.min()
    max_value = column.max()
    Q1 = column.quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = column.quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    min_whisker = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    max_whisker = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
    print('{} column:\nmin value: {}\nlower iqr: {}\nmax value: {}\nupper iqr: {}'
          .format(column.name, min_value, min_whisker, max_value, max_whisker), '\n')

# Create a function that will calculate the upper IQR
def upper_iqr(column):
    Q1 = column.quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = column.quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    max_whisker = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
    return max_whisker

Conclusion on price and parameters of interest

Based on the price of SUVs and sedans:

  • Numerical columns (scatter plots)
    • age & odometer: highest postitive correlation
      • as a vehicle gets older, it is likely to have more miles
    • age & mileage_per_year: highest negative correlation
      • as a vehicle gets older, it is likely to have more miles, but the mileage is spread out over more years. So the less miles per year, the older the car is likely to be.
    • age & condition_rank: negative correlation
      • the younger the car, the higher the rank. the older the car, the lower the rank.
    • odometer & conditoin_rank: negative correlation
      • cars with more total miles are more likely to have lower ranks
    • little to no trends:
      • condition_rank & mileage_per_year
      • odometer & mileage_per_year

    • paint_color

    • transmission type

Conclusions after code review

  • Categorical columns (box plots)
    • paint_color
      • SUVs
        • most SUVS have a median price between 5000 - 10000
        • orange and yellow SUVS have a median price above 15000 and 10000 respectively
        • black, grey, red, silver, and white SUVs have the highest priced outliers
      • sedans
        • most sedans have a median price between 3500 - 6500
        • orange sedans have the highest median price around 9000
        • grey, white, and yellow sedans have the highest priced outliers
    • transmission type
      • SUVs
        • automatic and other SUVs have a median price around 7500
        • manual SUVS have a median price above 10000
        • automatic SUVS have the highest priced outliers
      • sedans
        • manual and other sedans have the lowest median prices around 4500 and 3500 repectively
        • automatic sedans have the highest median price around 6500
        • automatic sedans have the highest priced outliers
